photo.description: Situated on a highland promontory overlooking the A1 and A167 roads into Tyneside, the Angel is highly visible. The amount of traffic on the road makes it one of the most viewed pieces of art in the world - seen by more than one person every second, 90,000 every day or 33 million people every year. The sculpture's creator designed its wings with a slight tilt of 3.5 degrees so it has the illusion of offering an "embrace" to those entering the Tyneside region.

photo.description: This giant steel sculpture stands at 66ft tall with a 175 foot wingspan, which makes it as wide as a Jumbo jet and broader than the height of the Statue of Liberty. Designed by Antony Gormley in a Lottery funded project which was completed in 2006, the angel has lived up to its name and become a true icon of industrial northern England. The sculpture takes inspiration from the region's history of ship building - these counties were once liner building powerhouses which gave birth to the likes of RMS Carpathia and the Mauretania in the great shipyards of Newcastle. Below the sculpture, massive concrete piles reach down some 20 metres deep and anchor it to the solid bedrock underground. It is made of weather resistant steel, containing a small amount of copper, which forms a patina on the surface that mellows with age. This means that the angel will have a lifetime of around a century before the ravages of corrosion take hold and begin to clip its wings. Click here for an aerial view of where this picture was taken.
